Why `std::mt19937_64`? Although computationally more complex than `std::minstd_rand`, benchmarking shows negligible difference. And it is the only 64-bit PRNG that I observed in the standard C++ library. Whilst we are here, we can mitigate the effects of some of the performance concerns by hoisting `std::uniform_real_distribution<>` outside of the function.

There are a lot of articles and [blog posts](https://v8.dev/blog/math-random) around the best way to implement random number generators. As such, this implementation doesn't strive for perfection. Just to be strictly better than the current implementation in having 64-bit seeded values instead of 32-bit, and not regress on speed from the existing implementation. This proposed implementation actually benchmarks 4% faster, presumably because `std::uniform_real_distribution<>` has to generate fewer 64-bit numbers than 32-bit numbers.

### Alternatives Considered

- To optimize for further speed, we could implement our own 64-bit version of a PRNG ([v8 source here](https://source.chromium.org/chromium/chromium/src/+/main:v8/src/base/utils/random-number-generator.h;l=119?q=XorShift128&ss=chromium)) but given Hermes core team doesn't want to take on un-necessary maintenance overhead, I don't think we should keep arbitrary implementations of PRNGs forked in our code.
- We could read directly from `std::random_device()` but it makes system calls and as you might expect, benchmarking reveals it to be much slower (see below). Worst still, it could theoretically block if the system doesn't have enough entropy.
- Instead of manually bit packing, an implementation leveraging `seed_seq` was explored that would ideally provide even more entropy, however the author of [this article](https://www.pcg-random.org/posts/cpp-seeding-surprises.html) asserts that 64 bits of seed seq data does not necessarily produce 64 bits of output. As such, we keep it simple with a single seed value so it is easier to reason with in the future.

